very different worlds. The papers in this volume pose the question of whether and how legal texts reflected such social differences within the Roman servile community. Did the legal system reinscribe social differences, and if so, in what shape? Were exceptions created only in individual cases, or did the legal system generate privileges for particular groups of slaves? Did it reinforce and even promote social differentiation? All papers probe neuralgic points that are apt to challenge the homogeneous image of Roman slave law. They show that this law was a good deal more colourful than historical research has so far assumed. The authors' primary concern is to make this legal diversity accessible to historical scholarship.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aHierarchie. 4aRömisches Recht. 4aSklaverei. 4apeculium. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Slavery.2bisacsh  aRoman law.  apeculium.  aslave families.  aslave hierarchies.1 aBuchwitz, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuongiorno, Pierangelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinkenauer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamauf, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClintock, Aglaia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchermaier, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchermaier, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStagl, Jakob Fortunat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08